description.et:
The poster presentation (final assessment): The final assignment for the course consists of a poster presentation. In the poster presentation, course participants present their analysis of one contemporary security challenge as it manifests itself in the context of a particular case.  The posters will be prepared in groups over the course of the semester. A list of topics will be provided by the course instructor together with detailed guidelines about the content and formatting requirements for the poster. 

The assessment of the poster and the poster presentation is differentiated (0-40 points). The poster and the poster presentation are assessed according to:

-	the detail and precision of the description and the explanation of the security issue;
-	the description of the central concept and its application to the case under consideration;
-	the visual presentation of content through the effective use of visualizations; 
-	adherence to the formatting requirements and sufficiency of sources;
-	the oral presentation of the poster.

Successful completion of the final assignment, and receiving the points for the final assignment, presupposes that each team member contributes sufficiently to the common effort. Should the individual contribution of a team member fall short of the agreed share, no points will be assigned to the team member..

The quizzes (interim assessments): The interim assessments consist of three quizzes which course participants will complete over the course of the semester. In the quizzes, students will be asked about the contents of the preceding lectures and the readings assigned in preparation for the lectures (e.g. key characteristics of contemporary security challenges, central concepts, or central debates/arguments in the field of Security Studies). 

The quizzes are assessed according to:
-	demonstrated familiarity with defining features/key characteristics of contemporary security challenges; 
-	demonstrated familiarity with key concepts in the study of international security;
-	demonstrated familiarity with central debates and arguments in the field of Security Studies and their correct assessment.
